This is honestly the single most awful take I have ever seen. We signed up and fundamentally created the ECHR for this sole purpose; so that when domestic governments, elected or not, choose to violate the rights of citizens, there is an accountable body to ensure standards are kept. Baring in mind the ECHR and EU are separate institutions and, as I hope you are aware, Strasbourg, under s.2 of the Human Rights Act 1998, has very little influence over domestic policy. This is simply to highlight an issue and the injunction  will be lifted when the case is heard or not. Lord Hailsham was right when he talked about elective dictatorship in the 70s and I for one am glad the ECtHR has decided to do what the Supreme Court and so many others have failed to do and put politics aside in the interests of people who, in this country, we owe a duty of care to. Awaiting the outcome of this case is not a burden or a nuisance or a lecture, it is following the procedure and standards we owe to the public. It is not virtue signalling either, it is upholding the rights we agreed to and signed up to, it is holding the government to account something Westminster, if even a place exists anymore, should be doing instead. This government is a disgrace and when your own former prime ministers, cabinet ministers, 148 of your own MPs, and 67% of the British public agree, it’s time to go; and shame on you for spouting nonsense about institutions and bodies when you clearly have no idea how they work in the real world.

All the issues stem from what's going on behind our global partners, for instance NZ is Labour, Australia is Labour and so it goes on, the Government need to sharpen their minds to deal directly with removing powers via international and also "secret" judges ruling on Britannia.

I also don’t need you telling what I should be buying them to make their lives easier, as you clearly do not have a bloody clue about real people, because if you think I’m going to my 80yr dad and 75yr mum to start HIT class, then you are  as delusional as you are judgmental on how you think everyone should be.

@nonorthwood I’m in my 70s and have battled through 4 different cancers, two of them Major, requiring major surgery and months and months of recuperation. I’ve worked since I was 13, had several jobs, working on Trading Estates and washing up as a young person, I worked as well as getting through a degree course at University, and never had the luxury of getting a Grant as so many others did of my age. After a prof career I had two jobs one of which I was self employed, running my own business. Unfortunately I was made redundant from a job I had for 20 yrs and have been made redundant twice. However I am still working for my own business.  My health is still an ongoing concern but I ‘manage it’ and refuse to be defined by the Old People who determinedly colour the view that they are all victims. I have never ever in my life claimed anything from the Govt either. I see all around me old people who have more and more expectations that the Govt will look after them. My past life of them absolutely NOT doing that ( no hand outs, nothing, except that brief Fuel Allowance) coloured my expectations of any future life help. Why on earth do you think I work so hard to keep so bloody fit? For gods sake? To stay out of frigging hospital, and to try not to be some chronic drain on NHS resources, better needed and spent on younger people! We ALL have had or had elderly parents to deal with.. or most of us. I KNOW how hard it can be. I had 5 hr trips to look after my mother who had Alzheimer’s , and refused to move out of her home. The cost of Private Care in her own home was phenomenal. We did NOT avail ourselves of Govt / Council social care, because having had it initially after her Stroke, we found the Care Workers were Systematically robbing her. This eventually involved the Police and a ‘trap’ was set which proved us right. She was also robbed whilst she was in Hospital recovering from her Stroke. 
I’m sorry you think I am such a horrible and nasty unpleasant person, and I apologise to you for sounding so harsh towards your efforts to support your parents and indeed your own parents who sound very decent people. Judge me if you wish. Your prerogative.
@susanwalker2033 Sorry I don’t have as much time on my hands as yourself, so will not be able to spend my day ready your life story

I know precisely how hard it can be to struggle against the forces of ill health and the difficulties surrounding old age. It must be worse to not anticipate the unexpected and esp if you rely on the expectation your govt to help you out. All that said, looking at your Profile I could well be talking to a robot.
